</ref>
* Maj. [[Jay Zeamer Jr.]]<ref>{{cite journal | last =Frisbee | first =John L. | title =Valor:Battle Over Bougainville | journal =Air Force Magazine  | volume =68 | issue =12 | pages = | publisher = | date= December 1985 | url= http://www.afa.org/magazine/valor/1285valor.asp | id = | accessdate =2007-01-16  }}</ref>

Other famous pilots and crewmembers include:
* [[Immanuel J. <U+201C>Manny<U+201D> Klette]] <U+2014> Second-generation German-American whose 91 combat missions were the most flown by any Eighth Air Force pilot in World War II.<ref>{{cite book | last =Freeman | first =Roger A. | title =Mighty Eighth War Diary | publisher =Motorbook International | date =1993 | location =St. Paul, Minnesota | pages =497-500| url = http://www.b17sam.com/8AFhero.html | isbn =0-87938-405-6 | accessdate =2006-12-20 }}</ref>
* [[Martin Caidin]] <U+2014> Author of ''Cyborg'', the story that formed the basis of ''[[The Six Million Dollar Man]]'' and the saga of the last transatlantic formation flight of B-17s ever made, ''Everything But The Flak''.
* [[Clark Gable]] <U+2014> Waist gunner on B-17 <U+201C>Eight Ball<U+201D> of the 359th Bomb Squadron.
* Captain [[Werner G. Goering]] <U+2014> American-born nephew of [[Nazism|Nazi]] ''[[Reichsmarschall]]'' [[Hermann Goering]], Commander of the German Luftwaffe.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.303rdbg.com/358goering.html| title = Werner G. Goering Crew <U+2013> 358th BS | accessdate = 2006-12-20 | last = Gobrecht | first = Harry D. | date = 2006 | work = Hell's Angels: Home of the 303rd Bomb Group (H) Association | quote = }}</ref>
* [[Colin Kelly]] <U+2014> Pilot of first U.S. B-17 lost in action.<ref>{{cite journal | last =Frisbee | first =John L. | title =Valor: Colin Kelly (He was a Hero in Legend and in Fact) | journal =Air Force Magazine  | volume =77 | issue =6 | pages = | publisher = | date= June 1994 | url= http://www.afa.org/magazine/valor/0694valor.asp | id = | accessdate =2006-12-20  }}</ref>
* Col. [[Frank Kurtz]] <U+2014> Olympic medalist in 1932 and 1936, and Pearl Harbor attack survivor. Commander of the 463rd Bombardment Group (Heavy), 15th Air Force, Celone Field, Foggia, Italy 1944-45; father of actress Swoosie Kurtz.
* [[Tom Landry]] <U+2014> American football player and coach.
* [[Norman Lear]] <U+2014> Radio operator, with the 463rd Bombardment Group (Heavy), 15th Air Force, Celone Field, Foggia, Italy; American Television Producer of "Sanford and Son", "Maude", "All in the Family" and more.
* Gen. [[Curtis LeMay]] <U+2014> Later head of the [[Strategic Air Command]] and head of the USAF.
* Col. [[Robert K. Morgan]] <U+2014> Pilot of ''Memphis Belle''.
* [[Gene Roddenberry]] <U+2014> Creator of ''[[Star Trek]]''.
* [[Robert Rosenthal (USAF)|Robert Rosenthal]] <U+2014> Assistant to the U.S. prosecutor at the [[Nuremberg Trials]], where he interrogated [[Hermann Goering]].
* [[Jimmy Stewart]] <U+2014> [[United States|American]] film actor, instructed in B-17s before flying combat in B-24s with the 8th Air Force, England; retired from Air Force Reserve a Brigadier General.<ref>{{cite book | last =Smith | first =Starr | title =Jimmy Stewart: Bomber Pilot | publisher =Zenith Press  | date =2005 | location =St. Paul, Minnesota | pages =| url = | doi = | isbn =0-76032-199-X | accessdate = }}</ref>
* [[Bert Stiles]] <U+2014> Short story author.
* [[Paul Tibbets]] <U+2014> Flew with the 97th Bombardment Group (Heavy) with both the 8th Air Force in England and the 12th Air Force in North Africa; later pilot of the B-29 [[Enola Gay]] dropping the atomic bomb on [[Hiroshima]], Japan.
* [[Robert Webb (pilot)|Robert Webb]] <U+2014> One of the youngest bomber pilots in the U.S. Army Air Forces.
* [[Smokey Yunick]] <U+2014> Award-winning motorsports car designer and premier NASCAR crew chief.

